        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Define the LineWithMeta schema — a Pydantic model for a single text line with its inline annotations (font styles, links, etc.). </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Text line data model with annotations. \par \b Input\/ \:  None (standalone model, references Annotation). \par \b Output\/ \:  Pydantic BaseModel <computeroutput>LineWithMeta</computeroutput> with text and annotations fields. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(7): pydantic.BaseModel; READS_DATA_FROM(8): Annotation] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>text is the raw line content, may be empty.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>annotations list may be empty but never None. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why store annotations as a flat list rather than nested? A: Flat list is simpler for JSON serialization and allows overlapping annotations (e.g., bold+italic on same range). \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Initial creation with semantic markup] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 10[Text line with inline annotations] =&gt; LineWithMeta \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[LineWithMeta]: LineExtractor =&gt; AnnotateTextRange =&gt; PassToCellOrNode </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
